It's a good investment as other multi paradigm language will support functional programming concept to a certain degree.
Imagine when you use Javascript without `this`, you will define your function by having all the required attributes as argument. That's basically the basic foundation of functional programming.

Lambda, or callback as you know it in Javascript, is just a way to compose function that usually used as parameters to do something against collection data structure. You use `map`, `reduce`, `fold`, `foldl`, etc, in place of `loop`.
Of course, I might be oversimplify it. But I hope you get the idea.

For what its worth this is my go-to template when teaching new Dev who try to wrap their head to replace loop with map-reduce-filter.

If the desired output is list with the same member as input, most likely you need Enum.map.
ie: [1,2,3,4,5] -> [2,4,6,8,10]

If the desired output is single data, most likely you need Enum.reduce.
ie : [1,2,3,4,5] -> 15

If the desired output is a list with fewer member, most likely it is Enum.filter.
ie: [1,2,3,4,5] -> [2,4]

What if it require combination of those?
Use pipe. 

Most of them never do loop again when writing JS or python.

Lisp -> “By the mid 1990’s I was a C++ expert, taught advanced C++ as an adjunct at NYU, and was a proponent and advocate of the benefits of static typing (but neglected the tradeoffs, sorry students!). I was happily discovering type parameterization tricks [Hickey 1996], running a const-correct shop etc.
However, over time, in my experience, the suitability-to-task of these statically typed class models for information systems programming was quite low, and the benefits of the type checking minimal, especially in addressing the number one actual problem faced by programmers: the overwhelming complexity inherent in imperative, stateful programming. As programs grew large, they required increasingly Herculean efforts to change while maintaining all of the presumptions around state and relationships, never mind dealing with race conditions as concurrency was increasingly in play. And we faced encroaching, and eventually crippling, coupling, and huge codebases, due directly to specificity (best-practice encapsulation, abstraction, and parameterization notwithstanding). C++ builds of over an hour were common. In the years immediately preceding work on Clojure I worked on the system to be used for the national exit poll in the U.S. This system involved automating large statistical models. Early on we decided that an imperative approach to doing the stats was a misfit, being not mathematical and also due to the expected concurrency throughout the system. After exploring F# for the task (and finding it insufficiently expressive), we decided to code the stats in C# like the rest of the system (this was a Microsoft .Net shop). I designed some custom immutable data structures whose use would be co-aligned with the figures in the statistical specifications (so statisticians who did not know C# could look at the code and understand it), and a functional library for manipulating the structures and doing the calculations. This was a great success, yielding much simpler code that we did not, and still do not, worry about. However, the resulting C# code was, in the eyes of both new and experienced C# developers, bizarre and non-idiomatic. Thus functional programming was a win, but FP in a non-FP language was not something I could see being widely applied.”

—— Rich Hickey, A history of Clojure. 

“Computer hardware has evolved dramatically in the last few decades. On a typical computer, storage and memory capacity have both increased a millionfold compared to the early 1980s. Nonetheless, standard industry practices in software development and mainstream ways of programming are not that different. Programming languages such as C++, Java, Python, and Ruby still typically encourage you to change things in place, and to use variables and mutate the state of a program, that is, to do things as if we were programming on a computer with a minimal amount of memory. However, in our quest for efficiency, better languages, and better tools, we reach for higher-level languages. We don't want to think about the computer's memory anymore, such as where a piece of information is stored and whether it's safe and shareable, as much as we don't want to know about the order of the instructions in the CPU. It is a distraction to the problems we are trying to solve, which are already complicated enough. If you have ever tried to do some multithreading in the languages cited previously, you will know the pain of sharing data between threads. Although, leveraging multicore CPUs with multithreaded applications is an essential part of optimizing a modern program's performance.”

—— Excerpt From The Clojure Workshop by Joseph Fahey, Thomas Haratyk, Scott McCaughie, Yehonathan Sharvit, and Konrad Szydlo. This material may be protected by copyright.

Mencoba menjawab yang ini
`Apakah memang spt ini? Ato cukup yg dimasukkan hanya plug routernya doang? Krn reponya kan diconsume di dlm controller, dan ini sdh didaftarim di dlm supervisor, ato emang harus didaftarin satu2 smua module yg implement GenServer?`

Iya module Plug(Endpoint) dan Ecto(Repo) di daftarkan di Supervisor agar process-nya dimulai sehingga dapat diakses seperti Process pada normalnya. Ketika Supervisor dimulai (start_link), maka supervisor akan memulai child prosesnya juga (Endpoint dan Repo). Seperti yang saya bilang, agar Kedua module itu berjalan dan dapat di passing massage ketika runtime.
